<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-675-796  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 675 796.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EXE  July 1990 v5 n2 p76(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Process Communications Ltd. (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Paying the price to build a greener career. (ethical concerns inemployment) (Career News - Recruitment)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Exchange Resources (management).andO;Topic:     Social ResponsibilityJob SearchEthicsSalaryReductionEmployment ServicesUnited Kingdom.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Computer staff are choosing to take salary drops of up to [British pounds]5000 to avoid working for firms with  unethical' business interests.andM;Companies working in the defence or nuclear sectors, or with interests inwhite South Africa, are being vetted through an ethical recruitment agency,Exchange Resources, based in Bath.andP;  Set up four years ago by a formercontractor who used to work in nuclear weapons development, the agencyattempts to place staff in companies that meet certain principled criteriaand which offer equal opportunities.andM;Some of the largest computer suppliers have appeared on the company'sblacklist, although there is some flexibility and, the company admits, someinconsistency.andP;  Candidates have been offered positions in particulardivisions of offending multinationals if the branch itself passes the test.andM;Tony Wilson, Founder and Managing Director of Exchange Resources, said:  Wetry to encourage individuals to work out what they want from their workinglives, and to go for it.'andM;He added: 'It's amazing how many people we get who are prepared to drop[British pounds] 1000, [British pounds] 2000 or [British pounds] 5000.andP;  Aspeople eventually realise that the world is limited and economies can't go onto grow at the rate they are now, they're happy to settle for less.'andM;This month, Exchange Resources will open two franchises.andP;  Wilson, who claimsthat the managing director of one multinational computer supplier had toldthe firm  never to darken their doorstep again', also intends to develop aformal vetting procedure to replace what is currently a fairly ad hoc system.andO;At the moment, the suitability of potential employers is determined fromtelephone calls, company reports, visits, and contact with groups like theAnti-Apartheid Movement.andO;</TEXT></DOC>